# pkg/map/apt.map — Arch package names → their Ubuntu/Debian equivalents.
#
# Format: <arch name> TAB <local name(s), space separated>   or   `-` to drop.
# Only DIFFERENCES belong here. A name absent from this file passes through
# unchanged, which is the common case — of HWE's 96 packages, 65 are spelled the
# same on both sides. See lib/distro.sh for why this is a map and not a second
# set of lists.
#
# Every entry below was verified against a real ubuntu:26.04 package index, not
# guessed. Re-check the WHOLE translated set at once — and with a resolve, not a
# lookup:
#
#     apt-get install -s $(… | _pm_translate)
#
# `apt-cache show <name>` is not enough: it answers for names that have no
# installation candidate at all, which is exactly how `bluez-utils` and `ruff`
# slipped through the first pass. Only the simulated install resolves.
#
# --- session plumbing ---
polkit	polkitd
python-jinja	python3-jinja2
qt5-wayland	qtwayland5
kvantum	qt-style-kvantum

# --- VM host tools (hwe vm; never installed by HWE, named only in `need` hints) ---
# Arch ships daemon and clients in one `libvirt`; Debian splits them. The
# -system flavour is what makes a working host (units, /etc/libvirt, the
# default network); virsh itself lives in libvirt-clients.
libvirt	libvirt-daemon-system libvirt-clients
# Arch's headless-QEMU bundle. qemu-img lives in qemu-utils; the emulator
# libvirt drives is qemu-system-x86.
qemu-base	qemu-system-x86 qemu-utils
# Arch names the package after the library that ships the tool; Debian's tool
# package is named after the binary itself.
libisoburn	xorriso
# virt-install needs no entry: resolute packages the tool under that very name
# (measured: the binary is in package `virt-install`), so it passes through.

# --- desktop components ---
# rofi 2.0.0 absorbed the rofi-wayland fork: it links libwayland-client and
# carries the zwlr_layer_shell_v1 symbols, so the plain package is the Wayland one.
rofi-wayland	rofi
mako	mako-notifier
networkmanager	network-manager
lm_sensors	lm-sensors
# Arch splits the daemon from the tools; Debian ships bluetoothctl inside bluez.
# apt knows the name `bluez-utils` from some dependency but has no candidate for
# it, so it must be named explicitly — `apt-cache show` is satisfied by such a
# name, only `apt-get install -s` reveals that nothing can be installed.
bluez-utils	bluez

# --- absent, with no equivalent in the archive ---
# Screenshot annotation. Two keybinds use it; they degrade to a plain screenshot.
satty	-
# Night light. Not in the archive; the PPA (HWE_HYPR_SOURCE=ppa) carries it and
# the hypr* pin already admits it. Without the binary the bar module hides and
# `hwe sunset` says why — nothing breaks.
hyprsunset	-
# Arch-only by definition (paccache, checkupdates…). Nothing to install.
pacman-contrib	-

# --- shell / tooling ---
openssh	openssh-client openssh-server
base-devel	build-essential
github-cli	gh
# The binary is `fdfind` on Debian — `fd` is taken. Anything calling `fd` by name
# needs to know that; the package is what this map is about.
fd	fd-find
python-pytest	python3-pytest
python-fonttools	python3-fonttools
python-numpy	python3-numpy
man-pages	manpages
# Debian splits the format's name from the tool's; the package carrying `xz` is
# xz-utils, while a package literally named `xz` does not exist there.
xz	xz-utils
# Upstream ships a GitHub Action; the standalone binary is not packaged.
actionlint	-
# Not in the archive at all (the only search hit is python3-scruffy, by
# substring) — and neither is uv, under any name (measured 2026-07-20). The
# sanctioned chain on this distro is pipx (packaged) → `pipx install uv` →
# `just lint-py` runs `uvx ruff`. Mapping ruff to pipx here would be the
# nerd-font trap again: install reports success and the tool is still absent.
ruff	-

# --- fonts ---
# Ubuntu packages the upstream families but NOT the Nerd-patched variants, and
# every HWE theme names a Nerd family in [font]. Mapping to the plain font here
# would silently give you a working font with no icons — worse than missing, so
# these are dropped and the Nerd fonts are installed from their own release
# archives instead (see _install_nerd_fonts).
noto-fonts	fonts-noto-core
noto-fonts-emoji	fonts-noto-color-emoji
# The text fallback IS packaged here, which is exactly why it was chosen.
ttf-jetbrains-mono	fonts-jetbrains-mono
# The icon font is not packaged anywhere in the archive. It is the one font HWE
# fetches itself on this distribution — one small file, attested — rather than
# the nine patched families below, which are dropped entirely.
ttf-nerd-fonts-symbols-mono	-
ttf-jetbrains-mono-nerd	-
ttf-cascadia-code-nerd	-
otf-geist-mono-nerd	-
ttf-intone-nerd	-
otf-monaspace-nerd	-
ttf-0xproto-nerd	-
ttf-lilex-nerd	-
ttf-ibmplex-mono-nerd	-
ttf-iawriter-nerd	-
